SIMPLE: glare
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Glare
<hw>Glare</hw> <pr>(gl⟦acir⟧r)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Glared</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Glaring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>glaren</ets>,
<ets>gloren</ets>; cf. AS. <ets>gl⟦ae⟧r</ets> amber, LG.
<ets>glaren</ets> to glow or burn like coals, D. <ets>gloren</ets> to
glimmer; prob. akin to E. <ets>glass</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To shine with a bright, dazzling light.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The cavern glares with new-admitted light.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To look with fierce, piercing eyes; to stare
earnestly, angrily, or fiercely.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And eye that scorcheth all it <qex>glares</qex> upon.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be bright and intense, as certain colors; to be
ostentatiously splendid or gay.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She <qex>glares</qex> in balls, front boxes, and the ring.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Glare</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Glare
<hw>Glare</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To shoot out, or emit, as a
dazzling light.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every eye⟦br⟧
<qex>Glared</qex> lightning, and shot forth pernicious fire.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Glare</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Glare
<hw>Glare</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A bright, dazzling light;
splendor that dazzles the eyes; a confusing and bewildering
light.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The frame of burnished steel that cast a <qex>glare</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A fierce, piercing look or stare.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>About them round,⟦br⟧
A lion now he stalks with fiery <qex>glare</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A viscous, transparent substance. See
<er>Glair</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A smooth, bright, glassy surface; <as>as, a
<ex>glare</ex> of ice</as>.</def> <mark>[U. S. ]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Glare</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Glare
<hw>Glare</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Glary</er>, and
<er>Glare</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>Smooth and bright or
translucent; -- used almost exclusively of ice; <as>as, skating on
<ex>glare</ex> ice</as>.</def> <mark>[U. S.]</mark><-- used generally of
reflections of the sun -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Glareolidae</ent>⟦br⟧
